Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment: So Star Wars the last Jedi looks promising. I like how this movie seems to expand the scope of the series instead doing the same story with new characters. I liked Force Awakens but it was way to derivative of New Hope. This movie does not seem to have the same problem. It's still going to be compared to Empire Strikes Back regardless. It's also great to see more ships then just X-wings on the side of the good guys. The space battle in Force Awakens really lacked variety. Even the New Hope space battle had Y-wings to ad some visual difference. Then there is Luke's line at the end of the teaser. "It is time for the Jedi to end." I think this is Luke deciding that the Jedi order and their methods have failed and it is now time for something new to come along. Earlier in the teaser he asks Rey what she sees and she says "Light. Darkness. The balance." and Luke response with "It's so much bigger." Are they finally doing away with the ridged black and white duality of the force? Did Luke gain some secret knowledge or a new understanding after he went into hiding? We'll find out in December.

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment: I love this version of Luke more then the legends, it brings to light the fact the many people over look. The sith were not the inbalance in the force that brought destruction the the galaxy, the jedi were. in Legends Luke attempted to bring back the order, but really it corrupted itself and eventually kicked him out. He died in exile from the Order. In this version he attempted to do the same thing. But he was unbalancing the force by doing so. Coupled that with a darker presence lurking deep in uncharted space. Luke bringing back the Jedi is a old outdated concept thought up by prequel era ideas. No mater how much we hate the prequels, the ideas brought forth in them were great. The Jedi order was pure light, they were blinded by their light and could not see the darkness that lurked before it was too late. Yoda even figured out before episode 3 that the Jedi were doomed. But stopping their destruction was not the correct path.

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment: OK so here is my theory. When Luke defeated Vader in ROTJ, he was very angry but he didn't turn to the dark side. Luke discovered that it's possible to achieve a great power if you can control both the dark side and the light (like Rey says in the trailer, that the "balance is so much bigger"). Then, in the Academy, he tried to teach this new approach to Ben Solo. Ben was unable to control the balance and was consumed by the dark side. Ashamed and considering this a personal defeat, Luke vanished. In time, he learned that as long as there are Jedi, there will be Sith, and viceversa, and the only way to really free the galaxy from the dark side is to achieve the balance that he is now teaching to Rey. A Jedi is pure light, hence, he thinks is time for the Jedi to end.

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment:
Disclaimer: i am not someone who knows literally everything to know about the star wars universe, and so i am sure someone is going to read this theory and tell me "oh no this or that is incorrect" if so sorry. This is just a simple theory from a fan of star wars.

So in the Rogue One movie we of course see the force vision, most prominent in it is the scene with Kylo and his first order. If you slow the film down enough in the background during one of the strikes of lightning, there is a building like structure seen in the top right area of the scene. I will reference this structure in a little bit. Based off the new teaser for Last Jedi, you see about 1.5 minutes in, Luke and R2D2 looking at a burning building. I believe first that this is a force vision Luke is showing Rey, in order to teach him what he knows. To first back up some, i believe this whole teaser trailer is supposed to show how Luke will teach Rey, in the beginning of the trailer, she is leaving the temple (and it looks like a cave, i think this is supposed to reference how Yoda taught Luke about his greatest fear in a cave) and in the background if you slow it down enough you hear Leia saying "save me Obi Wan" and then after that at the shot of Kylo Ren's shattered mask you hear the emporer saying either "it's you or the dark side" or "you survived the dark side" (i have literally replayed this at the slowest speed i can for an hour trying to determine exactly which it was and i convinced myself it could be both so you choose which one to believe). Right after you see a bookshelf of sorts, on a wooden wall and the wall first reminded me sort of Yoda's house, and there is a voice in the background. Unfortunately i could not exactly make out the voice but to me it sounded like Yoda. Then right after that, where presumably Rey is training with Luke's saber (i would believe it is Luke's) you hear "it's so much bigger" which i have two ideas on this line. Either this is someone telling Rey that this whole thing is so much bigger than ___, or it is possible someone trying to entise Rey to the dark side by saying this is so much bigger than ___ and you need to come to the dark side so i can show you kind of deal. Also sidenote at the shot of kylo ren where we hear "i only know one truth" i do not know who that is saying it, but i seriously think that is someone from another movie or game i have heard, it just sounds so familiar so if anybody knows please tell me thank you.  To continue, we return to the next shot of Luke and the burning building. First lets examine the outside of the building, near Luke you can see rubble, rocks, but if you look, you can also see green grass. And then around the building it appears as if there are three statues. One on the right, two on the left. And the shape of this building to me resembles a Jedi building. And as we know, the Jedi usually put statues near their temples so the statues would make sense. On the inside shot of this building we see troopers, but also we see i believe is what is to be Phasma in the middle. (So here is where i bring in outside information. At the big Star Wars celebration event, one of the people sorry i can not remember who so if you can find the footage that would be great, explained how many were disappointed in the lame way Phasma was treated before, so now they plan to make her super insanely awesome in this new movie. so that is why i believe that is Phasma). So to continue, this is what i presume to be a building for Jedi or some sort. In Rogue One, we see a building for just a brief second. if you compare these two, they look oddly familiar. In the scene from the force vision in Rogue One, you can even tell there is a statue in front of the building, as if you are looking at it from what is the left side from Luke's perspective (where  Luke sees two statues on the left side). Also in the force vision, there is grass, and water, and rain. So the atmospheres appear to be the same. Although one thing is off, and that is that in the force vision it is storming heavily, in the teaser scene it is not. But there is an idea for why. Also before i continue at the Star Wars event, Samuel L Jackson was there and he actually discussed how we know that jedi do not die from heights. This i believe is him referencing to the theory of how Mace Windu could be Snoke (go look that theory up it is actually really good) but what i think is that Mace Windu will be back in the movies, but not as Snokem but as himself. And so there is all the details so let me put this all together for you.

The teaser trailer is both a teaser for showing how Luke will train Rey, but also how he will explain his exile and why he has been in hiding. Basically here is how it goes. The jedi were being killed, he ran away. He eventually got to the last jedi temple as we see in the movie and trailer. Then as he waited, he studied all the relics there was to study in the temple, but he ran out eventually. Then he prematurely left his haven, in search for more relics, and possibly jedi that have been in hiding. But what happened was he returned to what i believe is his jedi school (the building we see in the force vision and in the teaser that is burning) to search for relics. I believe the place is destroyed by troopers and that he kills them, but he leaves when he senses Kylo there. So he escapes without meeting Kylo, which would make sense since he senses such a dark presence, and is trying to stay hidden. Luke then returns to the jedi temple and realizes he almost was caught and risked too much for knowledge, so stayed at the temple for the rest of the time being until Rey came along. And at the end of the teaser his line of "It's time for the jedi, to end..." is not the complete line. I think it ends with "...their exile/hiding" and so this whole trailer would then be him preparing her for recreating the jedi order. Which would make sense in what is Luke's prophecy. Because while everybody believed the great prophecy was to be Anakin, it is instead of Luke and how he will bring balance to the force, as in bring balance once more by brinding back the jedi and recreating the jedi order. 

That is my idea/theory on how this movie will go about, i am sorry if this is written really sloppily and not organised well, i will gladly take any support/criticism, and information. I hope you enjoyed reading this.

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment: I think what Disney doesn't realize is that the vast majority of the Star Wars fans up until now are ppl who're familiar with the series since the originals. What they're trying to do is revive the series in a manner that would attract new fans, using the same sequence the originals did, and making this continuation an original in a sense(which isn't appealing at all in my opinion since it perceives everything that's happened in the originals was pointless, they're back to square one).  It's because they assume that if they made a proper/different continuation to the series, (besides reusing the same ideas as the originals) it'll require new viewers to re-watch the originals, thus resulting in a high chance of many of them to drop the series. On the contrary though, this could be false, this could give them interest to watch the originals and learn more about the Star Wars universe, even the hype the old fans give this series alone could enrich the new viewers interest. however no one is sure how it'd turn out. I think the route they took was the safest to ensure the overall success of the continuation, new viewers would get a positive insight on the Star Wars universe and old fans would be delighted with franchises return. Just my own thoughts though

Comment:
I gotta admit though, I want to see even a glimpse of the (non-canon) Grand Master Skywalker from the novels.  The one that married the Emperor's Hand and had a son with her.  In some circumstances, the very mention of that man's name was the ultimate threat...

That said, there seems to be a glimpse of an older and very, very troubled Luke Skywalker here.  He seems to be a man who has endured years (decades?) where growth and suffering are nearly the same, and yet he has not followed in his father's footsteps and embraced the dark side.  But could it be, he has seen and learned enough to decide that "walking" with the Force is too dangerous an undertaking...for anybody?

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment: This will be the film that decides how future generations will view the Sequel Trilogy as a whole. TFA was a decent film with good production value but not strong enough to carry the entire trilogy; a Batman Begins if you will. And I don't see the third film being the strongest of the three: this is no Iron Man/new Star Trek scenario where if the production team screws up film #2 they can just move on to bigger things, and maybe later someone with an actual vision takes over. No, this film is it folks. We'll know this December whether the Sequel films go down in history as mediocre, or something worth remembering.

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment: To me the reason people hated TFA, and seemingly this one too (I loved TFA by the way) Is simply a case of memory association. You all loved Star Wars when you were kids, it was magic, exciting, the world was new, the possibilities were endless, you were blissful, you were happy.  Now you have grown up, and when you see a Star Wars film you are desperate to re-create those feelings. But you cant, because your an adult and life is unfulfilling. You''ll never reach the euphoria you had as a child watching Star Wars, you will just be let down, constantly unable to achieve those same feelings as before..much like a drug.  Your angry at Star Wars for not being as good as it was,  but really I think your just angry and disappointed with yourself. Open your mind, let go of hate and just enjoy the ride.

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment: This is how the new reboot of star wars should have started off. Luke skywalker has started a school for new Jedi and is training hundreds of new students and Kylo Ren is his padiwan learner. Rey comes to the school with the former storm trooper to deliver the little droid BB-8 too Luke and the rebel forces to tell them that a empire has been reformed and is being led by a sith lord known as Smoak. At some point in Kylo's training he starts having visions of the school being destroyed and everyone he knowns being killed, so he leaves and tries to kill Smoak on his own but gets captured and twisted to the darkside. Han Solo and Rey + others travel to the empire's star destroyer to get Kylo back and instead Han ends up dead at the hands of his own son who has fully crossed over to the darkside. The way did episode 7 was an exact copy of a new hope and none of it made any sense. Why did Kylo join the darkside, why did Luke stop his training, if the empire was destroyed or believed to be destroyed when the emperor was killed then why didn't Luke start a school for Jedi, who is Smoak and how is he connected to the Empire. None of these questions are ever explained during the film. Episode 8 could be a re-introduction of the empire and it's new emperor. Rogue One was awesome!. But episode 7 and 8 are garbage.

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment:
BREAKDOWN COMMENT MEGA THREAD:
THIS IS ALL SPECULATION AND IS PROBABLY NOT RIGHT BUT THOUGHT I'D SHARE

1. Obviously there are tons of quotes from characters that can be heard throughout
2. 0:11 Rey almost turns back to look into the cave at the very first start. Perhaps she sees something in the cave that unhinges her (like her vision at Maz's castle).
3.  0:34 A long shot but maybe Rey is using the force to practise on the waves?? Again, a long shot, probably just part of her montage
4. 0:47 This is obviously Leia looking at the map to Luke's whereabouts 
5. 0:53 lots of contradicting decisions on this. Could be Kylo's helmet because it looks more like it than Vader's (would explain why he isn't wearing his helmet later on). OR I originally thought as soon as I saw it that this was Vader's helmet and that Kylo destroyed it in anger that Anakin's lightsaber did not call for him, but instead Rey. This is most likely Kylo's helmet however.
6. 1:00 I literally have no clue on this I'm completely lost
7. 1:03 Seems like the Jedi symbol but the surrounding arcs look different. There is a cipher near the top left corner. 
8. At 1:12 Rey is seen to be training with Anakin's Lightsaber infront of Luke (being the bigger silhouette), however there is a smaller figure on the far right up the mountain. My speculation is that this is Maz Kanata. OR maybe this could be Yoda's force ghost now having looked at it more. Then again, how could a force ghost have a shadow??
9. 1:18 AT-AT Walkers can be seen on the horizon, I reckon this will be a First Order Variant and therefore be prone to being disabled via their legs. This would explain why they are not using T-47 Speeders.
10. 1:25 this could mean two things. As the Falcon was last shown on Ahch-To (Luke's island), where Rey and Chewbacca both took it. So, this could either mean Luke is on the Falcon with them going TO somewhere. Or it could also mean that Chewbacca has left Rey on Ahch-To and gone back to the resistance. As Chewbacca has not been in any shots with Luke/Rey, I believe he has left with the Falcon.
11. 1:27 as after this, Kylo is shown to have his lightsaber in a fighting form; I think it is the complete opposite and that this is again just Rey's training. On the other hand, she looks noticeably angry, maybe channeling her inner dark side like she did at the end of The Force Awakens. 
12. 1:28 First off, Kylo's eyes have a shade of yellow, similar to Darth Sidious' in Revenge Of The Sith. This debunks any theory that Kylo is a double-agent. Also, his scar is really reflective of Anakin's in Revenge Of The Sith.
13. 1:30 Obviously a flash back of the Knights Of Ren scene we saw in The Force Awakens. Linking back to earlier in the trailer, perhaps this is what makes Rey out of breath at the start (0:11). Also, in this shot, the old Jedi temple is seen to be on fire/in ruins probably due to the Knights Of Ren.
14. 1:31 As this is shown after the flashback scene, I believe this is a misdirect as it seems unlikely for Captain Phasma to be involved in the Knights Of Ren affairs in regards to killing off the new generation of Jedi. Could be completely wrong but it would just seem out of place for storm troopers to be there.
15.  1:40 Last shot, from my POV it seems like Luke is looking back talking to the camera rather than talking out into the open, most likely he is talking back at Rey after her training is complete in the caves.

NONE OF THIS WILL PROBABLY HAPPEN BUT THOUGHT I'D SHARE

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment:
Here are my thoughts on the last line Luke Skywalker says: "It's time for the Jedi to end."

As Rey says in the middle of the trailer, she sees a balance in the force, and this is probably what Luke is training Rey to become. Luke may be training her to become some sort of Grey Jedi, but I'm not sure. Luke knows there can't be any more Jedi because Jedi do not hold a balance, they fight for the light side, and as long as they exist, there will always be a conflict with the dark side. Luke wants to train Rey to learn the dark side and light side to keep balance in the force. If all force users learned both the dark and light side, what would they have to fight for? Could this mean Kyle Ren eventually learns the light side aswell? Could this be how the star wars series ends, with all existing force users learning both the dark and the light side to maintain peace in the galaxy while balancing the force?

If this were to be the main theme of the next two movies, I think it would be an excellent choice because of how much it could relate to our present day. There are so many differences within people that people constantly fight over, whether that be gender, race,  or sexual orientation, deep down inside we're all human. In the Star Wars universe, if all force sensitivity people learned the light and dark side they would no longer have a conflict because they could understand each other.

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment:
From a storytelling perspective, the sin that the prequels committed was making the Jedi a heroic character on their own, and Lucasfilm seems to be carrying it forward through the canon now. The hero's journey involves a character leaving home, embarking on a quest, and then meeting friends or guides who assist him along the way. Obi Wan and Yoda were the guides Luke met along his quest for self-actualization. They were masters of and confined to the realm of myth and, being so, knew how best to direct Luke towards his transcendence. 

As such, I can imagine generation after generation of soon to be Jedi embarking on their quests to continually right the galaxy. And, after completing their respective quests, they join the ranks among the supernatural guides for the next generation coming along. ...it's not Yoda and Mace going out to solve every dispute like almost literally glorified cops. 

Dark side users are those that fail to achieve transcendence. They are trapped in their own sense of justice, fueled by their emotions, and view the Jedi through the lens of their own shame. They're not more or less powerful. They're just unenlightened...and committed to it.

But when they declare that Yoda and the Jedi still have a quest, something to attain...they simultaneously declare that the Jedi are false prophets who never really aligned with the great mystery. They just have their dogma. The Sith have theirs. A or B. Pick your religion. And they become defined as polar opposites, bound in the tangible duality of good vs. evil. This is reinforced by the Bendu's dialog, by Ezra believing that they have to destroy the Sith without objection from Kanaan. I heard it in Maul's last lines. And I just heard in Luke's dialog.

So that, if they want to tear down what they think has been built up as the Church of the Modern Day Jedi, I'm ....okay... with that, except they have to bring down that roof on Yoda's head. He's confined to that space. And I love Yoda & Obi Wan way to much to diminish their status like that.

I'd rather they just admit and ignore the fault of the prequels in defining the terms that way and then pretend like Jedi were always the mystical guides who nudged other, actualizing heroes in the right direction.

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment:
So here are my thoughts on what the last Jedi Trailer and poster means. (Buckle up this could be a long one)

I do believe this means Luke will be the last Jedi of the Jedi order. Whether they will call the next generation Grey Jedi or not, I believe the next class will yield both the light and dark sides of the force. All this is based on the  on the prophecy of the Chosen Cne, and that the chosen one was Anakin Skywalker.

Here's why.

Vader brought balance the force at the end of a New Hope, but still failed. 
At the beginning of Episode one the force was unbalanced, the Jedi order had taken control of the galaxy and all but eradicated the Sith, thus making the force unbalanced. Anakin, by killing the of all Jedi, including Obi-Wan, the force was back in balance. Due to the fact there were only 2 Sith and Jedi remaining.

Here where things get interesting. Vader failed to complete the prophecy by the end of return of the Jedi, because he failed to turn Luke to the Dark Side, thus leaving the force unbalanced upon his death. If he would have turned Luke that would have left only one Sith and one Jedi surviving. Who would have been the last Jedi?......Leia. While untrained, Yoda even acknowledged her strength. With the presence of force ghosts, she could trained.

This brings us to the failure of Luke's Jedi order. It failed because the force requires balance and returning the Jedi to glory would have once again unbalanced the force. Therefore Kylo was guided to the Dark Side by the force itself. Upon killing Luke's padawans Kylo returned the balance. Thus making Luke the last Jedi. 

Luke realizes something was amiss in force from the perspective of the Jedi and decides to search for the first Jedi temple. What he finds will end the Jedi order.

He finds that balance must originate from the force users themselves, not from separate factions of the force.

Where's the proof you might ask. Two instances in the trailer and the poster itself. Let's start with the later. The poster shows the balance as it stands now. Luke the last Jedi, Kylo the last Sith. It also show the value as it will be. Rey wielding not only the bull saber of the Jedi, but also transforming into the red of the Sith. Indicating her ability to master both sides of the force.

The two instances in the trailer that lead me to this as well Luke himself saying the Jedi order must end. But also by asking Rey to reach out in the force and tell him  what she feels. Her answer reinforces this theory. She herself says she feel the light and the dark. Luke will teach her what he learned at the temple. He will teach her to master both the light and the dark side. Rey will be the first Grey Jedi.

Edit: I did not write this, however it was such a good explanation I had to share it.

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment:
Given that much of the Expanded Universe pre-Disney dealt with the idea that nearly all large scale conflict in the Galaxy was due to the schism between the Jedi and Sith and their various wars, Luke's comments taken in that context actually make sense.

If you think about it, the Jedi for millennia ONLY taught about the Light Side, ignored natural human (and other species') curiosity, and eschewed emotion, which ended up driving many apprentices to the Dark Side.

Perhaps Luke means to start a new way of training that doesn't involve monk-like asceticism, acknowledges darker emotions and teaches to control, rather than avoid or burying them. Looking back at the previous movies, one wonders why this never occurred to "wise" Jedi masters who saw so many padawans continually falling to the Dark Side.

Hell, look at some of their decisions:

Find the chosen one as a child, pin all your hopes on him and his emotional state to be clear and level, leave his mother to rot as a slave in the Outer Rim.

Find younglings, teach them about powerful space magic, ignore the biological drives and mood swings associated with puberty.

Define marriage as possession/attachment, and consider it a valid reason for expelling from the Order, ignoring that all of society uses the familial unit as a basis, or that having the support of family can enable one to endure hardships too heavy to bear alone.

Not bat an eye at or take a Jedi out of the field when he openly talks about not sleeping, having Force-fueled nightmares, obsesses over his mother, or basically tells the de facto head of the Order that he won't allow a dream about the death of a loved one to come true.

I mean, COME ON!

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment:
A Jedi trained in neither the absolute of the light, nor the dark, but one in the balance.
Luke will represent The Last Jedi (heheheh there's the name) to have walked the old path, the path of the pure Light side, while Kylo Res represents the path of the Dark side.
Luke's actions (the Light side) caused Kylo (The Darkside) to exist, and both sit on the polar opposite ends. Luke recognizes this as a fundamental flaw of the old Jedi Order but Rey still has hope to walk down the middle in balance and that's why she's at the center, the lightsaber splitting the two. She'll be balance back to the force, by being the Balance of neither here nor there. Despite the red and blue of the blade it has a neutral white light center, and goes from one end of the the Force spectrum to the other.
I don't think Rey will have many "dark side" tendencies, but she'll walk a darker path than Jedi before her, much more akin to Luke in RotJ.

Anakin was the chosen one, he was supposed to bring a balance to the force. Anakin kills all the Jedi. Sith are all powerful. No balance.

Luke fails to destroy Sith. Anakin takes over and kills the Emperor, then dies. No Sith left, Luke is the only Jedi. No balance.

I think Rey and Luke have to accept the dark side in them somehow, something every jedi always tried to reject.

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment:
I think if you look at the Jedi, they really aren't a very good role model or organization. They take children at very young ages, repress their emotions, teach them to kill, then tell them not to kill, and then tell them never love, never care, and turn them lose on the galaxy as Judges. I can't imagine a better way to breed resentment, anger, and hate, or depression and envy. All the emotions that lead you to the dark side. It's no wonder that the Sith keep coming from the ranks of fallen Jedi. 

I do hope Luke is saying that the Jedi (as the Jedi were) must end, and something new and better and more balanced must take it's place. You don't avoid negative emotions by ignoring all emotions, you just ball them all up and let them fester and grow. You have to deal with your emotions to maintain a balance.

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment: It's perfect. Luke is still and always will be predominantly light side, but what I think he wants to do us de-institutionalize the Jedi order and embrace a more balanced approach to the force much like the grey jedi. The dogma and hypocrisy by the late Jedi order by getting involved in a war while claiming to be keepers of the peace was their downfall. I think what Luke is trying to do is create more of a balanced in the force eliminating dumb rules like you can't marry, or you can't train if you are past a certain age, etc. Basically make it less culty. Remember that Snoke or Kylo are not considered Sith. They are something else entirely that obviously delves heavily in the dark side. I think this is something similar to what I believe Luke is going to try to do with a more benign approach and I'm all for it. This hypocrisy of the Jedi is highlighted when Obi-Wan says to Anikin "Only a sith deals in absolutes." which the Jedi had been operating in for millennia. That very absolution is what Luke has realized that causes force users like Darth Vader, Kylo Ren and countless other acolytes to fall into the lure of the dark side completely. It's the concept of parenting. When you teach your kids what is right by severely sheltering them, you are harming them by giving them an inability to abstain from the temptations that come knocking because they haven't been given a complete, balanced, and proper world view. This is what I call the forbidden fruit principle. Instead of shielding his future students from the dark side, I believe Luke has learned to expose them to their inner darkness in order to be triumphant against it. Much like Yoda did with Luke in the cave on Degobah.

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment: People keep complaining about the parallels between A New Hope/Force Awakens and Empire Strikes Back/The Last Jedi. Does no one see from this trailer that the parallels have been drawn to show WHY the ways of the Jedi fail? Because of the cyclical nature of events (Thriving Jedi (all light, no dark), collapse from within into empirical dark side (no light)) exemplified by the parallels in these movies' plot structure, Disney is taking us and Luke to the conclusion that an Order solely dependent on Light or Dark cannot be sustained. With Luke's quote at the end, it seems that the POINT of this trilogy is to have Luke introduce a superior, more natural method of dealing with the force; a method of balance between the Light and the Dark. Because this cyclical nature (the PURPOSEFULLY ESTABLISHED parallels) is entirely caused by polarization and imbalance. So the concluding point that differs from the original trilogy's is that it's wrong to ignore either side of the Force, but rather to balance them in order to stop the cycle of extremism.

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment: "It's time for the Jedi to end"... if that is indeed said by Luke, I think what he's saying is that true mastery of the Force is embracing both sides of it. In the prequels, the downfall of the Jedi was exactly that: they were so afraid of the Dark Side that they didn't even allow knowledge of it... and that's exactly why Anakin turned. He was being pulled by two fundamentally wrong ideologies, and one of them vowed to save his wife and allow him to embrace his power. So why not choose the Sith? I hope this is indeed what Luke means, because then the overall arc of Episodes 1-9 will be telling a pretty cool story where the last trilogy embraces both sides of the Force, each explored in the two respective trilogies before it. It will be DIFFERENT from the originals and prequels, and that's what matters to me. I hope the Last Jedi isn't just a copy of Empire like Force Awakens was of A New Hope.

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment:
Yes! End the Jedi. It's time for them to be replaced by the next incarnation of Force wielders. This is what I was hoping would happen ever since it was revealed that the Sith had been replaced by the Knights of Ren. The whole Star Wars universe has always followed a cyclical format, so it's only appropriate for the Jedi to go extinct and be replaced.

Also, those giant Resistance ships kinda remind me of very large B-wings, and I'm interested to see what those ships trailing red smoke are about. Maybe pirates of some kind? 

The only disappointment I have is that there was nothing on Snoke. Not even a brief shot of his face, or his robes or anything. I guess I'll just be glad the trailer didn't reveal much.

Comment:
yes, yes, yes.. good stuff! some food for thought to head into the weekend with!

Who doesn't get chills watching new SW trailers and the accompanying music score?

I definitely think there are strong indications to back up one of the popular theories that the concepts of Jedi vs Sith are inherently both bad, that you need both or the middle gray area to achieve balance in the Force, it's not just one side or the other.. So, does this mean the birth or beginning of a true gray force user philosophy, religion or order?.. I was going to say Gray Jedi, but I think they want to go away from the classic concepts associated with the term "jedi". I don't even know what they'd specifically call this in-between way of the force?

Sounds like Luke Skywalkder saying that the one certain thing is that the Jedi must end.

and, it looks like Kylo Ren destroyed his old mask.. don't need it anymore and just baring the scar face?

Pretty sure we will see a flashback of what Kylo Ren and the rest of his Knights of Ren did to Luke and his school, temple or academy and other students.. that's what it looks like in the trailer starting at about 1:30.. looks like a rear shot of the vision scene that Rey had in Ep.7 of R2-D2 and Luke crouching down to touch R2-D2.

Rey finds Luke, expecting him to be some big hotshot Jedi and what she finds is a bitter broken shell of a man

FO comes in, drops walkers miles away for whatever reason and the Resistance luckily has some not-really-designed-for-fighting ships lying around that get thrown at the ground forces to buy time for the important people to escape

Luke tells Rey about the Tragedy of -Darth Plagueis- the New Jedi Order and Rey says a few words that somehow make Luke snap out of his funk and he gives her a crash course in Jedi training (Pity her reliance on a staff doesn't mean she gets to use a double-bladed lightsaber, so she's gotta lean a whole new fighting style with Luke's old saber)

Meanwhile, the FO has kicked the Resistance's teeth in and gotten the information on where Luke Skywalker is and sends Kylo Ren to go finish him off

FO and Resistance engage in space battle while Luke, Rey and Kylo Ren duel

Somebody loses a hand

Comment: Can't wait! Showed just the right amount. Yes, I know the force awakens pulled a lot from A New Hope, but the idea was to bring the audiences into the world of the originals they grew up with and loved, and I can respect those that didn't like it as much for that, but I'm sure the franchise will now take a completely new direction to the OT. Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment: For those saying this doesn't make sense. There is clearly a very very subtle reveal of some key aspects that will be a part of the storyline, but don't forget, this is a teaser trailer. There isn't supposed to be a very obvious storyline because they are still in the editing stage which means the story will still change between now and the time the final cut is made. The point of a teaser trailer is to give us a quick taste in order to hype us up and get excited. It's not meant to be analyzed as a basis for the story. Official trailers however do include a sense of chronological story. So if you look at this through the lense that it is simply a taste, you may notice that it is actually a very beautiful teaser.

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment:
"Now, reach out. What do you see?" 
"Light... (JEDI), darkness .... (SITH), .... and BALANCE (GRAY)."

I can see it. Luke blames the Jedi code or the Jedi high council on why Ben turned to the dark side (almost like how Anakin did because he despised the high council) and lost his Jedi pupils. He believes in the light side of the force and he's definitely the last Jedi that the movie refers to since he's not training Rei to become a Jedi. Instead, I believe the film is focusing on how Luke will train Rei on how to use the force as a Gray Jedi. This is what Rei and Luke are talking about in the teaser. She feels the light side of the force, then the dark side of the force, and then the balance of the force... which is the strongest of the three. Luke even mentions saying that "It's so much bigger" saying that the balance of the force is where lies the truth. It's hard to tell where Rei stands because in episode 7 you see her losing herself to passion and anger and then at times submit to peace and serenity. This is where the Gray Jedi stands. The movie poster--Rei standing between the light and dark side. Even as the movie series as whole: I-III was about Anakin turning to the dark side and becoming a sith, IV-VI was about Luke turning to the light side and becoming a jedi, VII-IX will be about Rei turning into the balance of the force to destroy the sith and jedi and becoming gray.

Why don't I feel as much hype for this? I think it's because we just had a Star Wars movie barely a year and a half ago, and just had Rogue One a few months ago. The Force Awakens was the first great Star Wars film since 1980 with The Empire Strikes Back, and the hype for it was unreal. Then we had Rogue One which brought us back to the original trilogy period, and that was super hyped as well.

Now we have The Last Jedi, and my hype tank is getting used up. I don't feel as pumped up due to two straight years of Star Wars movie exposure. This trailer is absolutely beautiful....but I find myself not very excited.

Title: Star Wars: The Last Jedi Official Teaser
Comment:
not feeling it. Once again Star Wars is pushing this moral relativism that has no real place when you need that moral certainty of light and darkness, Jedi and Sith, to have balance and everyone else falls on the spectrum. Sure Luke could just be a cynic and lost faith and needs to regain it, but from this, Rebels, novels like Dark Disciple, and the rest of the new canon deathly afraid to properly tackle Force Users unless it's Ashoka (Gray moral relativism again,) Kanan and Ezra (where they are traversing those Gray waters too,) or a one-off mini-series like Obi-Wan/Anakin or Dark Siders (particularly Darth Maul and Darth Vader,) Jedi and Sith have largely been put on the periphiary when they are basically what Star Wars is about.

Film might still be good and it looks visually stunning once again, but I didn't feel the pulse like I did with the others.
